      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No worries, I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogies. Let's get back to the task at hand.\n\nAs for whether you can fix it yourself, I'd say it's possible, but it depends on your comfort level with DIY repairs. If you're comfortable with basic brake pad replacement and have some basic tools, you can definitely try to fix it yourself. However, if you're not confident in your abilities or if the issue is more complex, it's always best to take it to a shop.\n\nWhen checking the brake pads, look for the following:\n\n* Thickness: Check the thickness of the brake pads against the manufacturer's specifications. If they're worn down to 1/8 inch or less, it's time to replace them.\n* Wear indicator: Many brake pads have a wear indicator, which is a small metal tab that's exposed when the pad is worn down to a certain thickness. If you see this tab, it's a good indication that the pad needs to be replaced.\n* Pad material: Check the material of the brake pad. If it's a low-quality material or has been contaminated with debris, it may need to be replaced.\n* Pad surface: Check the surface of the brake pad for",
