      "content": "Even if the pads look okay, there could still be other issues causing the noise. Debris stuck in the brake caliper or wheel cylinder is a common culprit, and it's like a goblin hiding in the shadows, waiting to pounce on unsuspecting brake systems.\n\nWhen checking for debris, look for any signs of rust, corrosion, or mineral buildup on the brake components. Also, check the brake fluid level and condition. Low or dirty brake fluid can cause the brake pads to vibrate and produce noise.\n\nAnother possibility is a loose or worn-out brake caliper slide pin, which is like a goblin's favorite toy - it can get loose and cause all sorts of trouble. Check the caliper slide pins for any signs of wear or damage.\n\nAnd don't forget to check the brake hose for any signs of damage or wear. A loose or kinked brake hose can cause the brake pads to vibrate and produce noise.\n\nIt's also worth noting that a dirty or clogged brake rotor can cause the brake pads to vibrate and produce noise. So, even if the pads look okay, it's still worth checking the rotor for any signs of wear or damage.\n\nAs for grease, it's unlikely to be the cause",
